      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>833</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0022</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0022.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Basis">Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In the context of functional analysis and Hilbert spaces, there are several different notions of a basis:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Orthonormal basis:</fr:strong> In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is called an orthonormal basis if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">complete</fr:link>, meaning that the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is the entire space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>. Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal basis if for every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex> (expansion formula)</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex></fr:li> (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link>)</fr:ul>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Schauder basis:</fr:strong> A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_i\}]]></fr:tex> in a Banach space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is called a Schauder basis if every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> can be expressed uniquely as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{i=1}^{\infty } a_i x_i]]></fr:tex>, where the coefficients <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i]]></fr:tex> are scalars and the series converges in the norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Hamel basis:</fr:strong> A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> in a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is called a Hamel basis if every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  V]]></fr:tex> can be expressed uniquely as a finite linear combination <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _{i=1}^n a_i e_i]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i]]></fr:tex> are scalars. This is the algebraic notion of a basis, but in <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0005.xml" addr="FA-0005" title="Infinite Dimensions">infinite-dimensional</fr:link> spaces, Hamel bases are typically not useful for analysis because they are uncountable and the expansions don't involve convergence of series.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal bases</fr:link> in Hilbert spaces, the existence of such bases is guaranteed by the Gram-Schmidt process and Zorn's lemma, though they may be uncountable for non-separable spaces.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>834</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0020</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0020.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{x_n : n âˆˆ N\}]]></fr:tex> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> H is <fr:em>complete (note that this is <fr:strong>not</fr:strong> in the sense of a complete metric <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001C.xml" addr="FA-001C" title="Space">space</fr:link>)</fr:em>  if it satisfies <fr:em>any</fr:em> of the equivalent conditions (a)-(e) in <fr:strong>Theorem</fr:strong>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then the following conditions are equivalent:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(a)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_n, x \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(b)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} \langle  u_n, x \rangle  u_n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(c)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} |\langle  u_n, x \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>(This is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link>)</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(d)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[U] = H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(e)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0024.xml" addr="FA-0024" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Informally</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>For an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> in a Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to be a <fr:strong>basis</fr:strong> (or complete), it means that the set is "<fr:em>large enough</fr:em>" to represent any vector in the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> is <fr:em>complete</fr:em> if it's <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> is the whole space</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>835</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0024</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0024.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Maximal orthonormal set">Maximal orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is called maximal if there is no orthonormal set that properly contains <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is maximal if adding any non-zero vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  H \setminus  S]]></fr:tex> would destroy the orthonormality property. This means that for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  H]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||v|| = 1]]></fr:tex> that is not in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, there exists some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u \in  S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u, v \rangle  \neq  0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A key result in the theory of Hilbert spaces states that an orthonormal set is maximal if and only if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">complete</fr:link>, meaning that its <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> equals the entire Hilbert space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is maximal if and only if:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  x, e_i \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex> can be expressed as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-001A.xml" addr="FA-001A" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link> holds: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>836</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0027</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0027.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A complete (in the sense of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0020.xml" addr="FA-0020" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:link>) <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link>) of H is also called an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Altenately</fr:strong>: An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0024.xml" addr="FA-0024" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0021.xml" addr="FA-0021" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> of H.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>N.B.</fr:strong>: This notion of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> is <fr:em>not quite the same</fr:em> as in the <fr:em>finite dimensional case</fr:em> (although it is a legitimate extension of it).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>There are other, quite different, notions of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> in <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0005.xml" addr="FA-0005" title="Infinite Dimensions">infinite dimensions</fr:link>. See for instance '<fr:link type="local" href="FA-0025.xml" addr="FA-0025" title="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:link>' which arises in some settings</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Theorem:</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0026.xml" addr="FA-0026" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> has a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> orthonormal <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0022.xml" addr="FA-0022" title="Basis">basis</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>837</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000W</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000W.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Bessel's inequality">Bessel's inequality</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000T.xml" addr="FA-000T" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Then,</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(a)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} |\langle  u_n, x \rangle |^2 \leq  ||x||^2]]></fr:tex>;</fr:p>
            <fr:p>(can be seen as an <fr:em>infinite-dimensional Pythagorean theorem</fr:em>)</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(b)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_U \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \sum _{n=1}^{+\infty } \langle  u_n, x \rangle  u_n]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Q.xml" addr="FA-000Q" title="Convergent">convergent</fr:link> sum;</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(c)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x - x_U \in  U^\perp ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>(of course <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U^\perp ]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000V.xml" addr="FA-000V" title="Orthogonal complement">orthogonal complement</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>838</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>839</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0012</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0012.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Inner product space">Inner product space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An inner product space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> over the field of real or complex numbers, equipped with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  \cdot ,\cdot \rangle  : V \times  V \rightarrow  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The inner product satisfies the following axioms for all vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u, v, w \in  V]]></fr:tex> and all scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:strong>Linearity in the first argument:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  au + v, w\rangle   = a\langle  u, w\rangle   + \langle  v, w\rangle  ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Conjugate symmetry:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u, v\rangle   = \overline {\langle  v, u\rangle  }]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Positive definiteness:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  v, v\rangle   \geq  0]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  v, v\rangle   = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>From the inner product, we can define:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||v|| = \sqrt {\langle  v,v\rangle  }]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>A metric: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(u,v) = ||u-v||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The concept of orthogonality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> are orthogonal if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u,v\rangle   = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Common examples of inner product spaces include <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> with the dot product, the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex> with the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>-inner product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  f,g \rangle  = \int _a^b f(x)\overline {g(x)}dx]]></fr:tex>, and the space of square-integrable functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> is a complete inner product space.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
